{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654163"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:51:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:51:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18609"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18609"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11341"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76408"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11341"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18609"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61905"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10262"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26328"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26336"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76408"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESkeletal muscle contraction involves repeated interactions between myosin heads and actin filaments in a process requiring adenosine triphosphate (ATP). When ATP is depleted after death, muscles become rigid.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of ATP in muscle contraction?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Promotes actin-myosin binding","Enables myosin head detachment","Powers the force-generating stroke","Facilitates calcium ion release","Modifies troponin structure"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key role of ATP is that it \u003Cstrong\u003Eenables myosin head detachment\u003C/strong\u003E from actin filaments. When ATP binds to myosin heads, it breaks their strong attachment to actin, allowing the cross-bridge cycle to continue. This explains why muscles become rigid (rigor mortis) when ATP is depleted after death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromotes actin-myosin binding\u003C/strong\u003E - ATP actually breaks this binding rather than promoting it\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPowers the force-generating stroke\u003C/strong\u003E - The power stroke is triggered by phosphate release, not directly by ATP\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitates calcium ion release\u003C/strong\u003E - Calcium release is triggered by action potentials, not directly by ATP\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EModifies troponin structure\u003C/strong\u003E - Troponin changes shape in response to calcium, not ATP\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter causing detachment, ATP is hydrolyzed to ADP and phosphate, which prepares the myosin head for its next attachment to actin. The subsequent release of phosphate initiates the power stroke that generates muscle force.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["ATP binding to myosin heads is required to break their attachment to actin filaments during muscle relaxation","The power stroke of muscle contraction is triggered by phosphate release, not ATP hydrolysis","Rigor mortis occurs when ATP depletion prevents myosin heads from detaching from actin"],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevis